Let \mathcal {X} denote an alphabet of size m , and let \mathcal {P}=\{P_{1},\ldots ,P_{k}\} denote a collection of k distinct distributions on \mathcal {X} (every P_{i} can be identified with a pmf in \Delta _{m} ). Now, consider the following two-player game:
Player 1, representing adversary, chooses a distribution P from the set \mathcal {P}
Player 2, representing source coder, constructs a code according to the distribution Q \in \Delta _m without knowledge of P The goal of Player 2is to identify a Q that minimizes the worst-case redundancy {\mathcal {R}}^{*}\equiv {\mathcal {R}}^{*}({\mathcal {P}}):=\operatorname *{min}_{Q\in \Delta _{m}}\operatorname *{max}_{P\in {\mathcal {P}}}{\mathcal {R}}(P,Q)=\operatorname *{min}_{Q\in \Delta _{m}}\operatorname *{max}_{P\in {\mathcal {P}}}D_{\mathrm {KL}}(P\parallel Q).

